// =============================================================================
// VICTOR: CITY STRIKE â€” a complete third-person shooter on the Elpian VM
// =============================================================================
//
// This is a full, production-shaped TPS written in the Elpian Dart subset and
// executed by the Elpianâ†”Godot bridge: every engine object below â€” the city,
// the player, the enemies, the HUD, the audio â€” is created and driven purely
// through the reflective `GD.*` op protocol (see ../../../godot/README.md).
// The complete design document lives at elpian/godot/GAME_DESIGN.md.
//
//   * CITY â€” a procedurally assembled downtown built from Kenney's CC0 GLB
//     kits (assets/tps/): a 17Ă—17-cell road grid, 16 city blocks (tower /
//     mall / quad-building variants), parked cars, street lights, pavement,
//     boundary skyline, static-body collision for every structure.
//   * PLAYER â€” CharacterBody3D + capsule, an animated Kenney character with a
//     blaster attached to its hand bone, an over-the-shoulder SpringArm3D
//     camera with aim-down-sights zoom, sprint FOV kick, recoil and shake.
//   * COMBAT â€” two hitscan weapons (raycast through the physics space), pooled
//     tracers / muzzle flash / impact sparks / floating damage numbers,
//     headshots, magazine + reserve ammo, reloads.
//   * ENEMIES â€” three hostile archetypes (grunt / runner / heavy) with a
//     spawn â†’ chase â†’ attack state machine, line-of-sight checks, billboard
//     health bars, death animations, score and pickup drops.
//   * GAME FLOW â€” title menu â†’ wave combat â†’ intermissions â†’ game over â†’
//     restart; pause; regenerating health; kill feed; wave banners.
//   * MOBILE â€” full touch controls (virtual stick, look region, fire/aim/
//     jump/reload buttons) auto-enabled on touchscreen devices.
//   * AUDIO â€” every sound is synthesized offline into PCM and embedded below
//     as base64 AudioStreamWAV data: shots, hits, hurt, reload, death chime,
//     pickups, wave horn, and a looping city-wind ambience. Zero audio files.
//
// Engine-integrity rules this file follows everywhere (they are what make it
// run both on the real engine and against the mock in capi/tests/run_tps.rs):
//   1. every read from the host is guarded (`is Vector3` / `== true` / `is
//      Map`) and backed by a Dart-side prediction, so a null reply â€” the mock,
//      a paused frame â€” never breaks the simulation;
//   2. per-frame writes are coalesced into batches (one seam crossing per
//      subsystem per frame);
//   3. assets load only after `ResourceLoader.exists()` confirms them, with
//      procedural primitive fallbacks â€” the game is playable with no assets
//      imported at all.
import 'godot.dart';

